<subSubSection pageId="1" pageNumber="63" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1436,327,1468]" pageId="1" pageNumber="63">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,332,1371,1396]" inLineHeading="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="63" reason="1">Discussion.</emphasis>
The characters most valuable to distinguish 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Dellapé &amp; Montemayor" authorityYear="2012" box="[835,920,1372,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Aborsillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pora">
<emphasis box="[835,920,1372,1396]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="63">A. pora</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barber" authorityYear="1954" box="[989,1108,1372,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Aborsillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insignis">
<emphasis box="[989,1108,1372,1396]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="63">A. insignis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are the length of the rostrum and the coloration pattern. In 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Barber" authorityYear="1954" box="[486,605,1408,1432]" class="Insecta" family="Lygaeidae" genus="Aborsillus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="63" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insignis">
<emphasis box="[486,605,1408,1432]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="63">A. insignis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the rostrum is shorter, never reaching the abdomen, the scutellum is concolorous with the pronotum and the head, and the hemelytra lack a medial transverse dark brown band.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
